
TY  - JOUR
T1  - A TEST BETWEEN STOCK-FLOW MATCHING AND THE RANDOM MATCHING FUNCTION APPROACH*
AU  - Coles, Melvyn
AU  - Petrongolo, Barbara
Y1  - 2008/11/01
PY  - 2008
DA  - 2008/11/01
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1111/j.1468-2354.2008.00508.x
T2  - International Economic Review
JF  - International Economic Review
JO  - International Economic Review
SP  - 1113
EP  - 1141
VL  - 49
IS  - 4
PB  - John Wiley & Sons, Ltd
SN  - 0020-6598
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1111/j.1468-2354.2008.00508.x
Y2  - 2024/03/26
N2  - This article tests between the standard ?random matching function? approach and ?stock-flow? matching while controlling for temporal aggregation bias. Consistent with previous empirical work, the random matching function fits the matching data reasonably well. But match flows are more highly correlated with vacancy inflows than is consistent with the random matching approach. Instead the data support stock-flow matching, where unemployed workers match directly with suitable new vacancies as such vacancies come on to the market.
ER  - 

TY  - JOUR
T1  - IS ECONOMIC GROWTH GOOD FOR THE POOR? TRACKING LOW INCOMES USING GENERAL MEANS
AU  - Foster,             James E.
AU  - Székely, Miguel
Y1  - 2008/11/01
PY  - 2008
DA  - 2008/11/01
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1111/j.1468-2354.2008.00509.x
T2  - International Economic Review
JF  - International Economic Review
JO  - International Economic Review
SP  - 1143
EP  - 1172
VL  - 49
IS  - 4
PB  - John Wiley & Sons, Ltd
SN  - 0020-6598
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1111/j.1468-2354.2008.00509.x
Y2  - 2024/03/26
N2  - We propose the use of an alternative methodology to track low incomes based on Atkinson's ?equally distributed equivalent income? functions or ?general means? and present a new characterization to justify their application. To evaluate the effects of growth on lower incomes, growth rates are compared for two income standards: the ordinary mean and a low-income-sensitive general mean. The question is: How closely related are these two variables? After estimating the growth elasticity, we find that it is not significantly different from zero. Thus, it cannot be concluded that poorer incomes grow proportionately to increases in the average income.
ER  - 

TY  - JOUR
T1  - THE EFFECT OF MATERNAL EMPLOYMENT AND CHILD CARE ON CHILDREN'S COGNITIVE DEVELOPMENT*
AU  - Bernal, Raquel
Y1  - 2008/11/01
PY  - 2008
DA  - 2008/11/01
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1111/j.1468-2354.2008.00510.x
T2  - International Economic Review
JF  - International Economic Review
JO  - International Economic Review
SP  - 1173
EP  - 1209
VL  - 49
IS  - 4
PB  - John Wiley & Sons, Ltd
SN  - 0020-6598
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1111/j.1468-2354.2008.00510.x
Y2  - 2024/03/26
N2  - This article develops and estimates a dynamic model of employment and child care decisions of women after childbirth to evaluate the effects of these choices on children's cognitive ability. We use data from the National Longitudinal Survey of Youth to estimate it. Results indicate that the effects of maternal employment and child care on children's ability are negative and sizable. Having a mother that works full-time and uses child care during one year is associated with a reduction in ability test scores of approximately 1.8% (0.13 standard deviations). We assess the impact of policies related to parental leave and child care on children's outcomes.
ER  - 

